  "prompt_text": "Explain the difference between TCP's three-way handshake and UDP's connectionless communication.",
  "response_text": "To explain the differences between TCP's three-way handshake and UDP's connectionless communication:\n\nTCP's Three-Way Handshake:\n1. The three-way handshake is used to establish a connection between two endpoints.\n2. It includes three steps: SYN, ACK, and FIN.\n3. In each step, the sender sends a SYN packet to initiate the connection.\n4. The receiver responds with an ACK packet to acknowledge receipt of the SYN.\n5. If both parties agree on the port number, they can proceed to the next step.\n\nUDP's Connectionless Communication:\n1. UDP uses a simple connectionless protocol without requiring any acknowledgment or retransmission.\n2. It does not maintain state across connections; packets are sent immediately upon receiving them.\n3. This means that if a packet fails to reach its destination, it will be discarded.\n4. The sender must send a complete data segment before sending another packet.\n\nThe key differences are:\n- TCP requires a SYN-ACK sequence number for successful establishment.\n- UDP does not require a sequence number but still needs a checksum.\n- TCP maintains a connection state, while UDP does not.\n- TCP provides reliable delivery, ensuring data integrity, whereas UDP does not guarantee data delivery.\n\nThese differences make TCP more robust and reliable compared to UDP, especially when dealing with unreliable network conditions.",
